Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, stir in the @Basmati rice{150%g}, lower the heat to medium and pop a lid on the pan. Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat and set aside (still covered) for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> TIP: The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, trim the ends from the @carrot{1}(grated on a coarse grater) (no need to peel) then grate on a coarse grater. Remove the root from the @spring onion{2}(thinly sliced) and thinly slice. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Roughly chop the @salted peanuts{25%g}. In a small #bowl{}, combine the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @honey{15%g} and @water for the sauce{100%ml}. This is your sauce.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, fry the @British chicken thighs{4} (make sure you lay them out flat!) until golden on both sides and cooked through, ~{12-15%minutes}. Turn every few mins.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Transfer to a #plate{} and return the pan to medium heat. Add the red onion and cook, stirring often, until soft and sticky, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Add the sauce you made to the pan and bring to then boil. Lower the heat and simmer until reduced and slightly thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir occasionally. Return the chicken thighs to the pan for the last ~{1%minute} and turn to coat in the sauce. Warm the chicken through until piping hot.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the grated carrot, half the spring onion and half the peanuts. Season with a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Serve the rice topped with the sticky chicken, any sauce left in the pan, and the remaining spring onion and peanuts. Enjoy!